I hosted my Law Enforcement Advisory Board at my Willmar office. This committee is made up of around ten officers from across the Seventh District and they help keep me informed of their biggest concerns. At this meeting, there was a great deal of discussion about how local forces can support ICE. In particular, they noted they are having some difficulties because oftentimes they cannot detain someone that is here illegally until someone from ICE is present. As always, this was a very productive discussion and I greatly appreciated the Advisory Board's input so that when I'm back in D.C. I can work with my colleagues to find meaningful ways to support law enforcement at home.

I joined a roundtable discussion hosted by the Park Rapids Chamber of Commerce to talk about the work they are doing to make their community a better place. We talked about everything from tariffs to ongoing workforce housing concerns to rural broadband access. We also talked about the misinformation surrounding Medicaid in the One Big Beautiful Bill. The legislation does not cut funding for those who need it. It introduces targeted reforms to eliminate waste, fraud, and abuse within the program. This will ensure the resources are being directed to those who are truly eligible to receive them. This will preserve the long-term sustainability of Medicaid.

Today marks three years since the historic Dobbs Supreme Court Decision, taking a huge step towards building a culture that defends life. I remain committed to the pro-life mission to make sure every woman feels safe and empowered to choose life.

Today, I stood to condemn the attacks that killed Speaker Melissa Hortman and her husband, Mark, and injured Senator John Hoffman and his wife, Yvette. These victims committed themselves to public service and believed they were working to make their state a better place. There is no scenario in which that dedication should have cost them their lives.

Thank you to the city of Slayton for taking the time to meet with me! 
Like so many rural communities, Slayton has a serious childcare issue. There is only one center in the entire county, and it is at risk of closing. I understand how the loss of childcare can be devastating for families, businesses, and whole communities, and I am committed to doing everything I can to find solutions at the federal level. 
I introduced the Investing in Rural America Act to encourage private investment in our rural communities for things like childcare and community centers. And the One Big Beautiful Bill increases the child tax credits and prevents the biggest tax hike in history, easing some of the burdens on America's families.

I went to Pipestone to tour their JBS USA facility, which employs over 200 people who source livestock from 475 producers throughout the region. It was great to see the impact this business has on their area, from their product to their investments in community facilities like soccer fields, pickleball courts, and concession stands.

I met with the Granite Falls Chamber of Commerce and talked with local business owners about the issues impacting them most. One of the things we're doing at the federal level through the One Big Beautiful Bill is making the Death Tax exemption permanent, making it possible for family farms to pass their life's work down to the next generation.

I enjoyed touring @PURISfoods in Dawson, where we discussed a number of issues, including the lack of childcare in the area, which makes it difficult for families to make the move to call our wonderful rural communities home. The increased Child Tax Credits in the One Big Beautiful Bill would help these families, and my bill, the Investing in Rural America Act, would drive private investment for things like childcare and community centers in areas like Dawson.
